*** TI-80 Emulator ***
Version 0 alpha
By RANDY Ruler of Zexernet (Zeroko on ticalc.org) on 2011/10/12
Updated 2022/11/15 (confirmed that it works with ROM 3.0 & switched to CC0)
E-mail: RANDYRulerOfZexernet@gmail.com (please include "TI-80" in subject)

This program emulates a TI-80 calculator. Do not ask me for a ROM or where to get one. It is possible to dump it off the real calculator, desipte the lack of a link port. I hope to upload a ROM dumper soon, but I will first have to document it.

This emulator is in a very incomplete state. There are likely numerous ways to crash it or get it to behave in a manner inconsistent with a real TI-80. If you notice it producing incorrect behavior, please do tell me (& how you triggered it, of course).

You will probably need to re-compile it to get it to run, unless your environment is very similar to mine (64-bit Gentoo, kernel 5.15). It refused to link statically, & I am not going to fix it until other parts are more mature. This requires GTK+ 2.0 & the libti* used by TiLP 1.18 (at least). Type "make clean" followed by "make" & hope it works/chase dependencies, or else wait for a future version that is more portable.

Command-line arguments:
Optional: name of ROM file to load (should be 48 KiB)
Optional (but must include the previous): name of save state file to load

Features:
* Known to work with TI-80 ROM versions 3.0 & 4.0
* Virtual link with TiLP & other programs that can use the TiEmu virtual link
* Can load memory backups from a real TI-80
* Simulates power switch & removal of batteries (approximately)
* Debugger with realtime register display & breakpoints

Known inaccuracies:
* The timing is a bit off. I am not sure why.
* I am not sure of the correct values for reading 3FFE-3FFF (bytewise). They behave strangely on the real thing.
* LCD test mode is partially wrong
* Various unintentional/unknown interactions in the CPU

Planned features (no timeframe, no particular order):
* Disassembly pane in the debugger
* Ability to change register values
* Allow the user to choose which link interface to use
* Copy & paste of text
* Saving backups in a format that can be loaded onto a real TI-80
* Some way to load the ROM more easily
* Unlimited undo/redo (either a timeline or by individual keypad events)
* Clickable keypad image

